Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio.
• Debt is taken as Total Liabilities. In this case, the only liabilities are current liabilities:
  Accounts Payable + Taxes Payable = 2,000,000.00 + 1,143,833.89 = 3,143,833.89.
• Total Owner’s Equity (at end date) is given as 29,938,987.47.
• Debt to Equity Ratio = 3,143,833.89 / 29,938,987.47 ≈ 0.105 → Rounded to 0.11.

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin.
• Net Profit is given as 1,938,987.47.
• Total Revenue is given as 22,876,677.56.
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100
  = (1,938,987.47 / 22,876,677.56) × 100 ≈ 8.47%.

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.
• Operating Cash Flow is given as Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –16,772,398.72.
• Current Liabilities total = 3,143,833.89.
• Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Current Liabilities = –16,772,398.72 / 3,143,833.89 ≈ –5.335 → Rounded to –5.34.

Thus, the final answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.11",
    "Net Profit Margin": "8.47%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-5.34"
  }
}
